  <a href="#1" id="1">
   Danish studies of the drug Verapamil, a calcium channel blocker, show
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   that the drug reduces the chance of a new heart attack in patients recovering from a heart attack.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   This is the first trial
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   to indicate that calcium blockers may be helpful after a heart attack.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   Verapamil is about as effective as beta blockers in protecting people after heart attacks
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   and may be useful in instances where beta blockers cannot be used.
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   Many people do not tolerate beate blockers,
  </a>
  <a href="#8" id="8">
   especially those suffering from asthma and emphysema.
  </a>
  <a href="#9" id="9">
   Verapamil was effective in decreasing mortality in the first 12 to 18 months following a heart attack.
  </a>
